 The magazine is a completely separate component, both in physical terms in relation to the gun itself, and under the so-called "assault weapons ban" of 1994. If you look at the Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994 you'll see that the ban on "assault weapons" and the ban on "high capacity magazines" are two separate provisions of the overall law.

 And yes, despite what you might try to claim, the ban on so-called "assault weapons" was purely about cosmetic features, not physical differences. If the ban on "assault weapons" were only about function and overall design then I really don't see how those who wrote the bill could determine that some semi-automatics were considered "safe" to be owned, while others were "unsafe" to own and had to be restricted. Logically there's absolutely no sense to this argument.

 Mentioned features used for determining whether a firearm qualified as an "assault weapon" are as follows:

 `(B) a semiautomatic rifle that has an ability to accept a detachable magazine and has at least 2 of--

 `(i) a folding or telescoping stock;

 `(ii) a pistol grip that protrudes conspicuously beneath the action of the weapon;

 `(iii) a bayonet mount;

 `(iv) a flash suppressor or threaded barrel designed to accommodate a flash suppressor; and

 `(v) a grenade launcher;

 `(C) a semiautomatic pistol that has an ability to accept a detachable magazine and has at least 2 of--

 `(i) an ammunition magazine that attaches to the pistol outside of the pistol grip;

 `(ii) a threaded barrel capable of accepting a barrel extender, flash suppressor, forward handgrip, or silencer;

 `(iii) a shroud that is attached to, or partially or completely encircles, the barrel and that permits the shooter to hold the firearm with the nontrigger hand without being burned;

 `(iv) a manufactured weight of 50 ounces or more when the pistol is unloaded; and

 `(v) a semiautomatic version of an automatic firearm; and

 `(D) a semiautomatic shotgun that has at least 2 of--

 `(i) a folding or telescoping stock;

 `(ii) a pistol grip that protrudes conspicuously beneath the action of the weapon;

 `(iii) a fixed magazine capacity in excess of 5 rounds; and

 `(iv) an ability to accept a detachable magazine.'.

 All of these features, such as the adjustable stock, the pistol grip, the threaded muzzle, the flash suppressor, the bayonet lug, etc. these are all features that are purely cosmetic and neither add nor detract from the overall function of the gun in question. Regardless of what might be claimed, none of these features make the weapon anymore concealable (either when firing at night or when trying to hide under a coat), anymore controllable during rapid fire, anymore deadly, etc. they do none of that.

 I have seen many attempts by the gun control crowd on multiple websites to try and demonize these features, trying to paint them as some sort of lethality enhancers that can make a bullet deadlier than it would be from any other firearm of the same chambering and caliber. But what it all boils down to is bunk. It's nothing more than a scare tactic designed to prey on those who lack knowledge.

 Keep in mind that the Glock series of pistols have absolutely none of these features. It was never covered by the "assault weapons ban" of 1994. It was never prohibited from civilian ownership.

 All of this is irrelevant to a simple fact of reality: a gun is a deadly weapon. It's designed from the very beginning to be deadly in nature. There's no way one can successfully make it into anything else. It's not a non-lethal option. It's not politically correct in nature. The magazine itself plays absolutely no part in affecting this simple fact. The Glock in question was made no more deadly than it would've been if Loughner had been limited to only 10 round magazines (which he wouldn't have because they were never truly banned to begin with. There was no law stopping him from either buying or owning them.)

 A simple question really. Did the existence of the 30+ round magazine somehow give the 9mm rounds more velocity and better penetration qualities? Did the magazine improve ballistics to the point that they would be capable of defeating Kevlar vests should such be encountered? Did the magazine somehow make the diminutive 9mm round into a 100 percent lethal destroyer to all that was unfortunate enough to cross it's path?

 Of course the answer in these cases is a simple no. No magical qualities were bestowed upon the bullets thanks to the presence of this simple accessory. Therefore said magazine accessory makes no difference in what took place.

